  {
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "> I partially agree here. I think the helper should provide a way to get a meaningful subset of the state for serialization purpose, but not the serialization process itself. The serialization is part of the url mechanism as well. If we use other forms of storage, then the string wouldn't be meaningful but the sub object will always be.\n\nI would still add to the helper those two methods:\n- setStateFromQueryString\n- getStateAsQueryString\n\nMostly because this will allow us from the autocomplete.js project to generate urls that will be compatible with the urlsync widget of instantsearch.js (from an autocomplete suggestion, link to an instant search results, what we frequently do).\n\nOtherwise we would have to tell the autocomplete.js to somehow use the instantsearch.js project (and make it a dependency or something) to generate urls.\n\nThere will also be a good usage from the server side to do server side rendering and burn instantsearch.js urls in the html.\n\nAll of this is also doable if the methods are somewhere in instantsearch.js but I would find it weird from a usage POV (maybe show how it would be used from the instantsearch.js @bobylito?).\n\nI do not see why the state <-> querystring serialization mechanism should not be in the helper?\n\n> state -> partial state + partial state -> state >> Helper\n> partial state -> string vice versa, >> Widget\n\nDid not get it.\n",
